dict.string: If you already run or bicycle or do other aerobic exercise, you can start "Swim a Mile" plan right away. But if you’re coming straight from the couch to the pool, some preparation that begins at true zero would be useful, and this plan is for you then.

Swim any stroke at all, disregarding technique. As soon as you feel like stopping, flop over and do any kind of backstroke. When you tire, if possible still without stopping, switch to another stroke, such as sidestroke. If you do stop, keep the rest short until you are breathing somewhat more easily, but are not fully recovered.

Swim any stroke at all, disregarding technique. As soon as you feel like stopping, flop over and do any kind of backstroke. When you tire, if possible still without stopping, switch to another stroke, such as sidestroke. If you do stop, keep the rest short until you are breathing somewhat more easily, but are not fully recovered. Whatever you found most enjoyable may be continued, always increasing the distance using any stroke that makes it possible. A kickboard is sufficiently unpleasant to be useful, but stay away from pull-buoys. Your quads are big, demanding muscles and if you don’t use them because of the pull-buoy flotation, you defeat the whole purpose.

Swim any stroke at all, disregarding technique. As soon as you feel like stopping, flop over and do any kind of backstroke. Increase the amount of freestyle, but still change strokes rather than stop.

Rest for 6 breaths between 25s. If you are struggling with this week's excercise, don't worry. Just repeat it (using rescheduling), and third week should do the trick.

After completing this plan you will be ready for your first race! This plan has been created for someone who is already physically active but has minimal experience of cycling - you should be able to comfortably exercise for one hour.
Do some warm up and stretch excersies. It will help prevent injures.

Find a hill that takes at least five minutes to climb. Keep in the saddle the whole time. The hill should be steep enough that you cannot coast at any stage but not so steep that you find yourself labouring in your easiest gear.
Use the descent as an opportunity to recover in preparation for the next climb.Time to go down can be different, don't worry
